[ chuckles ]
son of a gun.

40:48.380 --> 40:50.415
â™ªâ™ª [ whistling ]

40:59.257 --> 41:02.727
Well, hello, all.
How we doing?

41:02.794 --> 41:04.729
Everything seems fine,
Dr. Craig.

41:04.796 --> 41:07.599
We wouldn't have it
any other way, would we?

41:09.267 --> 41:11.770
How're you feeling,
Mr. Broadwater?

41:13.938 --> 41:18.543
Great. That's terrific.
You have the look
of a survivor.

41:18.610 --> 41:21.046
No bleeding.

41:21.112 --> 41:23.982
Oh. And this must be young
master Broadwater.

41:24.049 --> 41:26.751
You know, you look
just like your Dad.

41:26.818 --> 41:29.921
You know what I have here?
This is a letter
from my son.

41:29.988 --> 41:34.025
He's grown up now and
he's already in medical school.
He's doing just fine.

41:34.092 --> 41:36.661
Eighth in his class.
Congratulations.

41:36.728 --> 41:40.198
And do you know
what he wants to become
when he's finished studying?

41:40.265 --> 41:42.367
A surgeon,
just like his old Dad.

41:42.434 --> 41:46.905
And someday, if you're lucky,
maybe he'll operate on you, huh?

41:46.972 --> 41:48.873
<i>Fathers and sons.</i>

41:48.940 --> 41:52.744
Well, you really do look
half-Well, Mr. Broadwater.

41:52.811 --> 41:56.081
<i>I'll be back tomorrow.
Mrs. Broadwater.</i>

41:56.147 --> 41:59.084
Your Dad's gonna be
just fine.

41:59.150 --> 42:02.220
I'm the only one
who could've saved his life.

42:03.254 --> 42:05.790
Excuse me. Dr. Craig?
Uh-huh.

42:05.857 --> 42:09.694
You know that question,
the one you asked me in surgery?
Yeah.

42:09.761 --> 42:13.765
Well, I, uh-- I thought
that maybe I, uh--
yeah?

42:13.832 --> 42:16.935
Well, I thought that
maybe now would be
a good--

42:17.002 --> 42:20.372
today, Ehrlich. Today.
Okay.

42:20.438 --> 42:23.074
The right originates
in right aortic sinus,

42:23.141 --> 42:26.378
runs to the right
beneath right auricle
to coronary Sulcus.

42:26.444 --> 42:28.380
Posterior
descending branches...

42:28.446 --> 42:31.650
down to the posterior
interventricular sulcus
to apex.

42:31.716 --> 42:35.387
The marginal branch Follows
right margin to apex--

42:35.453 --> 42:38.089
Excellent, Ehrlich.
Excellent.

42:44.829 --> 42:48.066
[ Softly ]
thank you.

42:48.133 --> 42:51.136
Son, is there anything you need
that we can get for you?

42:51.202 --> 42:55.907
Money. I need it to buy off
the orderlies and
the practical nurses.

42:55.974 --> 42:59.978
- It's the only thing
that gets them moving.
- You want to bribe them?

43:00.045 --> 43:02.814
Now, Lois.
It's not bribery, mother.

43:02.881 --> 43:05.283
<i>It's called tipping.</i>

43:05.350 --> 43:08.019
How much do you need, son?

43:08.086 --> 43:11.990
Well, the bigger the tip,
the better the service.

43:12.057 --> 43:13.958
A couple hundred.

43:16.294 --> 43:18.229
Here.

43:18.296 --> 43:21.366
We talked to that lawyer,
that Mr. Raveling.

43:21.433 --> 43:24.102
And he said that things
aren't as bad as they look.

43:24.169 --> 43:28.506
- No?
- No. He said there are
basically two ways to go.

43:28.573 --> 43:32.644
Since it's your first felony
charge, and you didn't intend
to hurt anyone--

43:32.711 --> 43:35.280
No one was supposed
to be in there
when the bomb went off.

43:35.347 --> 43:37.549
What's the second option?

43:38.817 --> 43:41.353
Well, it's, um,
temporary insanity.

43:41.419 --> 43:44.923
Mr. Raveling seems to think
he knows some psychiatrists
who will be sympathetic.

43:44.990 --> 43:48.860
<i>You tell that old bastard
we want to see
some results, right?</i>

43:48.927 --> 43:51.496
'Cause if he
can't do the job,
we'll get someone better.

43:51.563 --> 43:56.301
I know you can do it.
You're not gonna let those pigs
hang me out to dry, are you?

43:56.368 --> 44:00.071
Son, we're--
We'll do everything we can.
You know that.

44:01.439 --> 44:03.475
I know you will, Dad.

44:03.541 --> 44:05.677
You've never let me
down before.

44:09.781 --> 44:11.716
<i>[ Knocking ]</i>

44:11.783 --> 44:14.185
uh-huh?

44:14.252 --> 44:16.955
Dr. Westphall,
can we talk?

44:17.022 --> 44:19.424
I was just leaving.

44:19.491 --> 44:21.626
Okay. Sorry.

44:21.693 --> 44:23.628
Jack.

44:25.363 --> 44:28.633
My kids won't let me Tuck them
into bed anymore anyway.

44:29.768 --> 44:31.736
What's up?

44:34.005 --> 44:38.176
I saw Mr. Mcallister
outside his wife's room.

44:40.111 --> 44:43.782
Boy, what a shame.
Is she gonna be all right?

44:45.684 --> 44:49.821
Everybody keeps asking me
that, and I keep saying
the same thing-- I don't know.

44:49.888 --> 44:52.257
You know, it's ironic,
isn't it?

44:53.958 --> 44:56.895
Reinhardt sets off a bomb.

44:56.961 --> 44:58.930
Kills two people,

45:00.131 --> 45:02.367
maybe a third,

45:02.434 --> 45:04.536
and he's gonna be okay.

45:04.602 --> 45:08.707
And we do everything we can
to make sure he's gonna be okay.

45:08.773 --> 45:13.712
And the only thing he feels
for you or me or Mcallister
or his parents...

45:13.778 --> 45:16.348
or... anybody...

45:18.550 --> 45:21.052
is Contempt.

45:21.119 --> 45:23.955
This obnoxious,
withering sarcasm.

45:24.022 --> 45:28.326
<i>And we do everything
we can to make him okay.</i>

45:28.393 --> 45:30.428
We can't choose
our patients.

45:35.300 --> 45:38.870
When I got out of college,

45:38.937 --> 45:42.307
my folks wanted me
to go to law school,

45:42.374 --> 45:45.343
but my wife and I
had other plans.

45:45.410 --> 45:49.447
We bought a Van and
traveled around the country
for a year and a half.

45:49.514 --> 45:52.851
We said we wanted
to experience things,

45:52.917 --> 45:56.921
but the truth is
I just didn't want to go
to law school.

45:56.988 --> 45:59.724
And the reason I didn't want
to go was because I knew...

45:59.791 --> 46:01.926
I didn't want to defend
someone who's guilty.

46:01.993 --> 46:06.297
Now, I understand why lawyers
have to defend guilty people...

46:06.364 --> 46:09.467
and why doctors have to treat
terrible human beings.

46:09.534 --> 46:11.603
<i>But I've gotta
tell you something.</i>

46:11.670 --> 46:14.472
The reasons aren't
good enough.

46:14.539 --> 46:16.541
Because in order for me
to be a good doctor,

46:16.608 --> 46:20.045
I've gotta separate
my feelings from myself.

46:21.413 --> 46:25.050
And that scares
the hell out of me.

46:25.116 --> 46:29.220
Because if I don't know what
I feel, I don't know what I
believe in or who I am.

46:31.122 --> 46:34.592
You know, uh,
when I first
started my internship,

46:34.659 --> 46:37.996
I was a very
happily married man,

46:38.063 --> 46:40.632
but I fell in love
with one of my patients.

46:40.699 --> 46:43.335
She didn't know it.

46:43.401 --> 46:46.271
I don't think she knew it.
Maybe she did.
I don't know.

46:46.338 --> 46:48.406
But I'll tell you something.
I suffered.

46:48.473 --> 46:51.109
I used to carry
her x-Rays around with me.

46:51.176 --> 46:52.978
[ Laughing ]

46:53.044 --> 46:55.013
That's True.

46:57.148 --> 46:59.751
Oh, I don't know.
Sometimes, you know,

46:59.818 --> 47:01.753
doctors starting out
care too much.

47:01.820 --> 47:05.657
And then they get older,
they don't seem
to care enough and...

47:07.459 --> 47:11.529
they seem to become inured
to their own feelings
or to other people's pain.

47:11.596 --> 47:13.965
<i>It's a--</i>

47:17.802 --> 47:19.938
I'm gonna go home.

47:24.609 --> 47:26.911
You know somethin'?

47:26.978 --> 47:30.515
I think you would've made
a damn fine Lawyer.

47:30.582 --> 47:33.218
<i>Good Night.
Good Night.</i>

47:44.596 --> 47:47.265
Half day,
Dr. Westphall?

